            <title><stale>Friday Week 6</stale> Monday Week 7 - The Six Trigonometric Functions</title>
<page>
        <objectives>
          <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Define the reciprocal trigonometric functions and evaluate them at special angles.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Recognize the graphs of the reciprocal trigonometric functions.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Introduce and use the Pythoagorean Identity (this is important!)
                </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </objectives>
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    We're now familiar with the sine, cosine, and tangent functions. There are three more trigonometric functions that are occasionally useful. These are the reciprocal trigonometric functions.
                </p>
            </introduction>

<definition>
    <statement>
        <p>
           Given an angle <m>\theta</m> in the unit circle, we make the following definitions:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\sec(\theta) = </m><fillin characters="5" />
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\csc(\theta) = </m><fillin characters="5" />
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\cot(\theta) = </m><fillin characters="5" />
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </statement>
</definition>

<p>
    <term>Warning:</term> These functions are not the same as <m>\sin^{-1}</m>, <m>\cos^{-1}</m>, and <m>\tan^{-1}</m>. Those are inverse functions.
</p>

<paragraphs>
    <title>Evaluating the Reciprocal Functions</title>
<p>
    Find the indicated values:
</p>
<ol>
    <li>
        <p workspace="0.5in">
            <m>\cot\left(\frac{\pi}{4}\right)</m>
        </p>
    </li>
        <li>
        <p workspace="0.5in">
            <m>\sec\left(\frac{11\pi}{6}\right)</m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p workspace="0.5in">
            <m>\csc\left(\frac{5\pi}{3}\right)</m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p workspace="0.5in">
            <m>\csc\left(\frac{11\pi}{6}\right)</m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p workspace="0.5in">
            <m>\sec\left(-\frac{\pi}{2}\right)</m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p workspace="0.5in">
            <m>\cot\left(-\frac{13\pi}{6}\right)</m>
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
    
</paragraphs>

</page>
