<fact xml:id="pythagorean-id">
    <title>The Pythagorean Identity</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            If <m>\theta</m> is any angle, then 
            <md>
                \sin^2(\theta) + \cos^2(\theta) = 1.
            </md>
            
        </p>
        <p workspace="2in">
            <term>Explanation:</term>
        </p>
    </statement>
</fact>

<paragraphs>
    <title>Uses of the Pythagorean Identity</title>
    
</paragraphs>
<ol>
    <li>
        <p workspace="2in">
            We can derive a similar identity for the secant and tangent functions.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p workspace="2.5in">
            We can find values of <em>any</em> trigonometric functions given the value of one and a quadrant using these identities. For instance, suppose <m>\theta</m> is in quadrant I and <m>\sec(\theta) = 17</m>. Find the values of the other five trigonometric functions.
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>


